            <h2>
              Module 1: Introduction to Computer Networks
              <span class="badge">Foundation</span>
            </h2>
            <p>
              Learn what a computer network is, why we need it and the basic components
              used to build modern networks.
            </p>

            <table>
              <thead>
              <tr>
                <th style="width:25%;">Module</th>
                <th>Topics</th>
                <th style="width:20%;">Level</th>
              </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">1.1 Networking basics</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
                    <li>What is a computer network? Need & advantages</li>
                    <li>Client‚ÄìServer vs Peer-to-Peer networks</li>
                    <li>Bandwidth, latency, throughput, jitter (concept)</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
                <td><span class="level-pill">Beginner</span></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">1.2 Types of networks & topologies</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
                    <li>LAN, MAN, WAN, PAN, CAN (overview)</li>
                    <li>Topologies: Bus, Star, Ring, Mesh, Hybrid</li>
                    <li>Campus network, branch network, data center</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
                <td><span class="level-pill">Beginner</span></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">1.3 Network devices overview</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
                    <li>Hub, Switch, Router, Bridge, Repeater</li>
                    <li>Modem, Access Point, Firewall (basic idea)</li>
                    <li>NIC, patch panel, cables (UTP, fiber)</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
                <td><span class="level-pill int">Intermediate</span></td>
              </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </article>

          <!-- Module 2 -->
          <article class="card" id="module2">
            <h2>
              Module 2: OSI & TCP IP Reference Models
              <span class="badge">Theory</span>
            </h2>
            <p>
              Understand the layered approach of networking and the OSI and TCP IP models
              used to design protocols.
            </p>

            <table>
              <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Module</th>
                <th>Topics</th>
                <th>Level</th>
              </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">2.1 OSI model</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
                    <li>7 layers and their functions</li>
                    <li>PDU at each layer (bits, frames, packets, segments)</li>
                    <li>Encapsulation & decapsulation process</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
                <td><span class="level-pill">Beginner</span></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">2.2 TCP IP model & protocols</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
                    <li>TCP IP layers and comparison with OSI</li>
                    <li>Reliable vs connectionless transport protocols (concept)</li>
                    <li>Application layer protocols used for web, file transfer, name resolution, address assignment</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
                <td><span class="level-pill int">Intermediate</span></td>
              </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </article>

          <!-- Module 3 -->
          <article class="card" id="module3">
            <h2>
              Module 3: IP Addressing & Subnetting
              <span class="badge">Core Skill</span>
            </h2>
            <p>
              Master IPv4 addressing, subnetting, CIDR and basic IPv6 concepts
              used in every real network.
            </p>

            <table>
              <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Module</th>
                <th>Topics</th>
                <th>Level</th>
              </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">3.1 IPv4 basics</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
                    <li>IPv4 structure: network & host portion</li>
                    <li>IP classes A, B, C, D, E</li>
                    <li>Public vs Private IP ranges, APIPA</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
                <td><span class="level-pill">Beginner</span></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">3.2 Subnet mask & CIDR</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
                    <li>Default masks for Class A/B/C</li>
                    <li>CIDR notation: /8, /16, /24 etc.</li>
                    <li>Network ID, Broadcast ID, usable hosts</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
                <td><span class="level-pill int">Intermediate</span></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">3.3 Subnetting practice</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
                    <li>FLSM (Fixed Length Subnet Masking)</li>
                    <li>VLSM (Variable Length Subnet Masking) ‚Äì concept</li>
                    <li>Real subnetting examples for office networks</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
                <td><span class="level-pill int">Intermediate</span></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">3.4 IPv6 overview</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
                    <li>Need for IPv6, address format</li>
                    <li>Types: Global, Link-local, Unique local</li>
                    <li>Shortening rules and basic usage</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
                <td><span class="level-pill">Beginner</span></td>
              </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
            <p class="tip">
              <strong>Lab idea:</strong> Give a network (e.g. 192.168.10.0/24) and ask
              students to create subnets for different departments.
            </p>
          </article>

          <!-- Module 4 -->
          <article class="card" id="module4">
            <h2>
              Module 4: Switching & LAN Concepts
              <span class="badge">Layer 2</span>
            </h2>
            <p>
              Understand LAN switching, MAC addressing and how frames move inside
              a local network.
            </p>

            <table>
              <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Module</th>
                <th>Topics</th>
                <th>Level</th>
              </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">4.1 MAC & ARP</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
                    <li>MAC address format and purpose</li>
                    <li>Address resolution within the LAN</li>
                    <li>Address table & basic troubleshooting</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
                <td><span class="level-pill">Beginner</span></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><span class="module-label">4.2 Switch operations</span></td>
                <td>
                  <ul class="topic-list">
